The beauty of soft science fiction is that any explanation with enough semi-logical waffling to justify it will be fine. It's all in service to the end result. Personally I'm fond of far future altered humanity because it's relatively rare, it explains anthropomorphism well, and I find the idea of a widely spread, non-traditionally developed humanity attractive on its own. Plus, I guess there's something platonically kinky in the idea of baseline humans being regarded with this mix of awe, danger, and backwardsness. Kind of like how we'd look at a Medieval knight or Roman gladiator being dropped into the modern age.

But I might go this way in a science fiction setting of my own (coming soon, by which I mean, probably not so soon). The idea of a Subnautica type world where the alien systems start cranking out sexy critters is attractive in its own right. It's got that weird edge of not being quite sure if you can trust this system that's giving you aquatic honeys that a non-pervert shouldn't be attracted to anyway.
